        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12112",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "I am still undecided about the value of having RFC 822 dates with a zone component localized to the timezone identified by the _Locale property of an instance of Zend_Date.  Accurately determining a timezone for a particular locale seems nearly impossible, since many locales have multiple timezones.\n\nHowever, determining the time offset using:\n{code}mktime(0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 1970) - gmmktime(0, 0, 0, 1, 2, 1970){code}\n\nseems reliable, although the server's local time might not be the timezone desired by the developer and might not be related to the _Locale property of any particular instance of Zend_Date.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=gavin",
                        "name": "gavin",
                        "displayName": "Gavin",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-01-05T12:48:57.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-01-05T12:48:57.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12114",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Having a look at the specification\nhttp:\/\/www.ietf.org\/rfc\/rfc0822.txt\nat page 25 you see the specification of the RFC 822 date.\n\nAnd the timezone offset is explicitly specified... it's also returned by PHP when you use date(DATE_RFC822);\nEven some browsers return a timezone difference instead of GMT.\n\nThe locale itself is not given for determinating the timezone offset... it's passed for the new date object to set the locale of this object. So you can extract a localized date of a RFC date for example.\n\nrelated to this code\n<code>\n$result = $date->setArpa('Sat, 03 May 01 00:00:00 +0100');\n$this->assertSame($result->get(Zend_Date::RFC_822),'Thu, 03 May 01 01:00:00 +0200');\n<\/code>\n\nIn general this date would be false... because the 03.May 2001 is a thursday and not a saturday...\nalso the timezone offset of 1 hour is wrong, because we have summertime at this date... so +1 becomes +2.\nsetArpa uses the timezone which is set for the script. You can set your timezone offset with\nphp.ini, by using date_timezone_set or by using Zend_Date->setTimeZone.\n\nAnd the timezone for all tests is set to Europe\/Paris.\n\nThe input is only fixed, otherwise we would have to throw an exception because the date is illegal.\n\nBtw: \nThe timezone offset is sometimes usefull... so you can determinate where in the world a user is located... some will set a different language, but noone will set a different timezone for his client ;-)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-01-05T14:00:24.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-01-05T14:00:24.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12165",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Also to mention:\n\nThe RFC_822 parameter was included because of PHP's new date constant DATE_RFC822\n\nBut PHP does also not produce RFC conform output.\n\nsetting the timezone to Europe\/Paris produces a timezone setting of CET for \ndate(DATE_RFC822);\n\nBut CET is not supported by RFC 822...\n\nOn the other side +0000 as Zend_Date produces it, is supported by RFC 822...\nThe question now is how we should behave.\n\nParsing input RFC conform, or behave like PHP ??\n\nI delay this issue to 0.8 because we need to clarify this with the PHP developer team.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-01-06T04:46:48.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-01-06T04:46:48.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12215",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Work has been stopped until response from PHP devteam related to PHP itself not RFC 822 conform",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-01-13T12:58:28.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-01-13T12:58:28.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/12510",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Fixed with SVN 3190 for the I18N branch.\n\nRemember:\n\nPHP itself gives wrong otput for DATE_RFC822 until PHP 5.2.2. So PHP's and the frameworks outputs are not equal... the Framework outputs the correct RFC822 string.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/framework.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-02-04T15:40:26.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-02-04T15:40:26.000+0000"
                }
            ]
